Exercise 13.1: What is a copy constructor? When is it used?

Answer:
Copy constructor is a constructor that the first argument is a reference to to the class type and all other arguments
has default values.

It is used in a number of scenarios:
1)When a function returns an object by value.
2)When assigning, using the operator =.
3)When a function has an argument that is passed by value(a non reference argument).
4)When initialising using the following braces : {}.

Exercise 13.2: Explain why the following declaration is illegal:

Sales_data::Sales_data(Sales_data rhs);

Answer:
It is illegal since rhs is sent by value, before calling the constructor we would have to call the same constructor
which will cause the constructor being called indefinitely.

Exercise 13.3: What happens when we copy a StrBlob? What about
StrBlobPtrs?

Answer:
When we copy StrBlob it will call the copy constructor for shared_ptr which will raise it's count while copying StrBlobPtr
the copy constructor will be called which copied the pointer to the weak_ptr and so the count will stay the same.

Exercise 13.4: Assuming Point is a class type with a public copy
constructor, identify each use of the copy constructor in this program
fragment:
line 1: Point global;
line 2: Point foo_bar(Point arg)
line 3: {
line 4: Point local = arg, *heap = new Point(global);
line 5: *heap = local;
line 6: Point pa[ 4 ] = { local, *heap };
line 7: return *heap;
}

Answer:
The copy constructor will be called on:
line 2 --> foo_bar receives arg by value so the copy constructor of Point will be called before entering the function.
line 4 --> when assigning arg to local the copy constructor will be called and when creating the object that heap will point to from global.
line 6 --> when initialising pa from {local, *heap} and when copying local inside the {} braces.
